        "summary": "### Summary of Core Topics, Concepts, Principles, and Equations\n\n#### 1. Perceptron\n- **Concept**: A single-layer neural network used for binary classification.\n- **Equation**: \\( f(z) = 1 \\) if \\( z \\geq \\theta \\), where \\( z = W^T x \\).\n- **Activation Condition**: The perceptron gets activated if the weighted sum of inputs is greater than or equal to the threshold \\( \\theta \\).\n\n#### 2. Non-Linearly Separable Problems\n- **Concept**: Problems where a single straight line (or hyperplane) cannot separate the classes.\n- **Principle**: A single perceptron cannot solve non-linearly separable problems because it can only model linear decision boundaries.\n\n#### 3. Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) for XOR Function\n- **Concept**: MLP is a feedforward artificial neural network that models non-linear relationships.\n- **Activation Function**:\n  \\[\n  f(x) = \\begin{cases}\n  0, & \\text{for } x < 0 \\\\\n  1, & \\text{for } x \\geq 0\n  \\end{cases}\n  \\]\n- **Implementation**: Use an MLP with one hidden layer to model the XOR function.\n\n#### 4. Sigmoid Function and Its Derivative\n- **Equation**: \\( f(z) = \\frac{1}{1 + \\exp(-z)} \\)\n- **Derivative**:\n  \\[\n  f'(z) = f(z) \\cdot (1 - f(z))\n  \\]\n\n#### 5. Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)\n- **Concept**: An algorithm used in speech recognition to align input sequences with output sequences.\n- **Applications**: Speech recognition, handwriting recognition, etc.\n\n#### 6. Probability in Language Models\n- **Concept**: Calculating the probability of a word sequence.\n- **Equation**: \\( P(\\text{you} | \\text{How are}) = \\frac{P(\\text{How are you})}{P(\\text{How are})} \\)\n\n#### 7. Markov Chains vs. Hidden Markov Models (HMM)\n- **Markov Chains**: A stochastic model describing a sequence of possible events where the probability of each event depends only on the state attained in the previous event.\n- **Hidden Markov Models**: A statistical model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.\n\n#### 8. Viterbi Algorithm\n- **Concept**: An algorithm to find the most likely sequence of hidden states (the Viterbi path) that results in a sequence of observed events.\n- **Application**: Used in HMM for weather prediction, speech recognition, etc.\n\n#### 9. Types of HMM Models\n- **Discrete HMM**: Observations are discrete symbols.\n- **Continuous HMM**: Observations are continuous variables, often modeled using Gaussian distributions.\n- **Left-Right HMM**: A type of HMM where the state transitions are constrained to move from left to right.\n\n### Knowledge Graph \n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD;\n    A[Perceptron] --> B[Single Layer Neural Network];\n    A --> C[Binary Classification];\n    B --> D[Linear Decision Boundary];\n    C --> E[Activation Function];\n    E --> F[Threshold];\n    G[Non-Linearly Separable Problems] --> H[Single Perceptron Limitation];\n    I[Multi-Layer Perceptron] --> J[XOR Function];\n    I --> K[Non-Linear Relationships];\n    L[Sigmoid Function] --> M[Derivative];\n    N[CTC] --> O[Speech Recognition];\n    N --> P[Handwriting Recognition];\n    Q[Probability in Language Models] --> R[Word Sequence Probability];\n    S[Markov Chains] --> T[Sequence of Events];\n    U[Hidden Markov Models] --> V[Unobserved States];\n    W[Viterbi Algorithm] --> X[Most Likely Sequence];\n    Y[Types of HMM] --> Z[Discrete HMM];\n    Y --> AA[Continuous HMM];\n    Y --> AB[Left-Right HMM];\n```\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD;\n    A[Perceptron] --> B[Single Layer Neural Network];\n    A --> C[Binary Classification];\n    B --> D[Linear Decision Boundary];\n    C --> E[Activation Function];\n    E --> F[Threshold];\n    G[Non-Linearly Separable Problems] --> H[Single Perceptron Limitation];\n    I[Multi-Layer Perceptron] --> J[XOR Function];\n    I --> K[Non-Linear Relationships];\n    L[Sigmoid Function] --> M[Derivative];\n```\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD;\n    N[CTC] --> O[Speech Recognition];\n    N --> P[Handwriting Recognition];\n    Q[Probability in Language Models] --> R[Word Sequence Probability];\n    S[Markov Chains] --> T[Sequence of Events];\n    U[Hidden Markov Models] --> V[Unobserved States];\n    W[Viterbi Algorithm] --> X[Most Likely Sequence];\n    Y[Types of HMM] --> Z[Discrete HMM];\n    Y --> AA[Continuous HMM];\n    Y --> AB[Left-Right HMM];\n```",
